You must give a grand
and glorious party for me.

1003
01:24:00,287 --> 01:24:02,874
- A party?
- Yes, Father, please!

1004
01:24:03,073 --> 01:24:05,343
It's high time
I met all your friends...

1005
01:24:05,633 --> 01:24:08,025
...and they met me.
Don't you agree?

1006
01:24:08,292 --> 01:24:10,434
- I see what you mean.
- Oh, please!

1007
01:24:10,694 --> 01:24:13,729
Children, it's bedtime.
Come now, say good night.

1008
01:24:14,631 --> 01:24:15,877
Good night, Father.

1009
01:24:16,074 --> 01:24:18,790
- Good night.
- Good night, Baroness Schraeder.

1010
01:24:19,018 --> 01:24:20,512
Good night, Father.

1011
01:24:23,372 --> 01:24:25,129
Good night, Uncle Max.

1012
01:24:26,959 --> 01:24:29,992
It'll be my first party, Father!

1013
01:25:01,220 --> 01:25:03,741
- Captain.
- Herr Zeller. Baroness Schraeder.

1014
01:25:03,942 --> 01:25:06,942
- Good evening, Herr Zeller.
- Baroness.

1015
01:25:08,201 --> 01:25:10,568
How do you do? Good evening.

1016
01:25:30,357 --> 01:25:33,654
Did you notice the obvious
display of the Austrian flag?

1017
01:25:40,442 --> 01:25:42,167
The women look so beautiful.

1018
01:25:42,428 --> 01:25:43,704
I think they look ugly.

1019
01:25:43,965 --> 01:25:45,721
You're just scared of them.

1020
01:25:45,950 --> 01:25:48,089
Silly, only grown-up men fear women.

1021
01:25:48,671 --> 01:25:52,088
- I think the men look beautiful.
- How would you know?

1022
01:26:07,197 --> 01:26:09,139
Liesl, who are you dancing with?

1023
01:26:09,341 --> 01:26:10,903
Nobody.

1024
01:26:11,680 --> 01:26:13,504
Oh, yes, you are.

1025
01:26:15,875 --> 01:26:17,306
May I have this dance?

1026
01:26:17,508 --> 01:26:19,900
I'd be delighted, young man.

1027
01:26:26,412 --> 01:26:28,968
Why didn't you tell me
you could dance?

1028
01:26:29,200 --> 01:26:33,937
We feared you'd make us all dance.
The von Trapp Family Dancers.

1029
01:26:38,168 --> 01:26:39,794
What are they playing?

1030
01:26:40,025 --> 01:26:42,548
It's the Laendler.
An Austrian folk dance.

1031
01:26:42,748 --> 01:26:45,783
- Show me.
- I haven't danced since I was little.

1032
01:26:45,981 --> 01:26:47,869
You remember. Please?

1033
01:26:48,127 --> 01:26:49,984
- Well...
- Please.

1034
01:26:50,210 --> 01:26:52,348
All right. Come on over here.

1035
01:26:52,836 --> 01:26:55,553
Now you bow and I curtsy.

1036
01:26:56,454 --> 01:26:59,273
- Like this?
- Fine. Now we go for a little walk.

1037
01:26:59,499 --> 01:27:02,051
One, two, three. One, two, three.

1038
01:27:02,350 --> 01:27:06,763
One, two, three, step together.
Now, step hop, step hop.

1039
01:27:06,993 --> 01:27:09,547
Now turn under. Not quite.

1040
01:27:09,746 --> 01:27:13,548
This way. Hop step, hop.
And under.

1041
01:27:14,199 --> 01:27:15,825
Kurt, we'll have to practice.

1042
01:27:16,055 --> 01:27:17,485
Do allow me, will you?

1043
01:28:42,238 --> 01:28:44,029
I don't remember anymore.

1044
01:28:46,116 --> 01:28:48,222
- Your face is all red.
- Is it?

1045
01:28:49,510 --> 01:28:51,520
I don't suppose I'm used to dancing.

1046
01:28:54,123 --> 01:28:56,033
Why, that was beautifully done.

1047
01:28:56,301 --> 01:28:58,124
What a lovely couple you make.

1048
01:28:58,317 --> 01:29:00,359
It's time the children
said good night.

1049
01:29:00,624 --> 01:29:01,901
We'll be in the hall.

1050
01:29:02,128 --> 01:29:04,881
- We have something special prepared.
- Right!

1051
01:29:05,171 --> 01:29:06,286
Yes, come on!

1052
01:29:12,860 --> 01:29:15,098
All that needless worrying, Georg.

1053
01:29:15,357 --> 01:29:18,261
You thought you wouldn't find
a friend at the party.

1054
01:29:21,057 --> 01:29:24,508
- A bit chilly out tonight, isn't it?
- Oh, I don't know.

1055
01:29:24,706 --> 01:29:26,652
It seemed rather warm to me.

1056
01:29:30,666 --> 01:29:31,845
Ladies and gentlemen.

1057
01:29:32,555 --> 01:29:36,488
The children of Captain von Trapp
wish to say good night to you.

1058
01:29:50,040 --> 01:29:53,787
There's a sad sort of clanging
From the clock in the hall

1059
01:29:53,982 --> 01:29:57,562
And the bells in the steeple too

1060
01:29:57,824 --> 01:30:01,689
And up in the nursery
An absurd little bird

1061
01:30:01,891 --> 01:30:04,227
Is popping up to say "coo-coo"

1062
01:30:04,454 --> 01:30:06,048
Coo-coo

1063
01:30:06,313 --> 01:30:07,493
Coo-coo

1064
01:30:07,722 --> 01:30:09,796
Regretfully they tell us

1065
01:30:09,995 --> 01:30:11,305
But firmly they compel us

1066
01:30:11,565 --> 01:30:14,502
To say goodbye

1067
01:30:14,703 --> 01:30:19,791
To you

1068
01:30:22,871 --> 01:30:26,614
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, good night

1069
01:30:26,808 --> 01:30:30,522
I hate to go
And leave this pretty sight

1070
01:30:37,508 --> 01:30:40,706
So long, farewell,
Auf Wiedersehen, adieu

1071
01:30:41,350 --> 01:30:44,736
Adieu, adieu
To you and you and you

1072
01:30:51,792 --> 01:30:55,437
So long, farewell
Au revoir, auf Wiedersehen

1073
01:30:55,700 --> 01:30:59,478
I'd like to stay
And taste my first champagne

1074
01:30:59,703 --> 01:31:02,036
- Yes?
- No.

1075
01:31:06,203 --> 01:31:09,718
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye

1076
01:31:10,045 --> 01:31:13,846
I leave and heave a sigh
And say goodbye

1077
01:31:14,049 --> 01:31:17,880
Goodbye

1078
01:31:20,809 --> 01:31:23,778
I'm glad to go

1079
01:31:24,010 --> 01:31:26,762
I cannot tell a lie

1080
01:31:27,084 --> 01:31:29,957
I flit, I float

1081
01:31:30,224 --> 01:31:33,542
I fleetly flee, I fly

1082
01:31:43,195 --> 01:31:48,699
The sun has gone to bed

1083
01:31:48,928 --> 01:31:52,510
And so must I

1084
01:31:52,706 --> 01:31:55,010
So long

1085
01:31:55,237 --> 01:31:57,694
Farewell

1086
01:31:57,894 --> 01:32:03,081
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye

1087
01:32:03,341 --> 01:32:08,463
Goodbye

1088
01:32:09,137 --> 01:32:14,478
Goodbye

1089
01:32:14,710 --> 01:32:21,305
Goodbye

1090
01:32:21,499 --> 01:32:29,656
Goodbye

1091
01:32:34,470 --> 01:32:37,124
Extraordinary!
What they'd do at the festival.

1092
01:32:37,353 --> 01:32:39,745
Young lady,
I must have a word with you.

1093
01:32:40,715 --> 01:32:44,548
Georg, you won't let this girl
get away. She must join the party.

1094
01:32:44,815 --> 01:32:47,118
- No, really l...
- Stop. Stop it now.

1095
01:32:47,378 --> 01:32:50,195
- Georg, please.
- You can if you want to, fraulein.

1096
01:32:50,421 --> 01:32:52,811
I insist.
You will be my dinner partner.

1097
01:32:53,015 --> 01:32:54,839
This is business.
Franz...

1098
01:32:55,096 --> 01:32:58,132
...set another place next to mine
for Fraulein Maria.

1099
01:33:00,222 --> 01:33:02,842
- Whatever you say.
- It appears to be all arranged.

1100
01:33:03,614 --> 01:33:05,406
- It does.
- I'm not suitably dressed.

1101
01:33:06,434 --> 01:33:07,864
You can change. We'll wait.

1102
01:33:11,334 --> 01:33:14,151
Captain, you must be very proud
of your youngsters.

1103
01:33:14,344 --> 01:33:15,175
I am, thank you.

1104
01:33:15,434 --> 01:33:19,813
Is there a more beautiful expression
of what is good in our country...

1105
01:33:20,045 --> 01:33:23,345
...than the innocent voices
of our children?

1106
01:33:23,729 --> 01:33:25,039
Oh, come now, baron.

1107
01:33:25,265 --> 01:33:28,881
Would you have us believe that Austria
holds a monopoly on virtue?

1108
01:33:29,751 --> 01:33:33,713
Herr Zeller, some of us prefer
Austrian voices raised in song...

1109
01:33:33,913 --> 01:33:36,215
...to ugly German threats.

1110
01:33:37,244 --> 01:33:40,726
The ostrich buries his head
in the sand...

1111
01:33:40,926 --> 01:33:43,743
...and sometimes in the flag.

1112
01:33:44,257 --> 01:33:48,285
Perhaps those who would warn you that
the Anschluss is coming, and it is...

1113
01:33:48,548 --> 01:33:52,099
...would get further with you by setting
their words to music.

1114
01:33:52,298 --> 01:33:56,775
If the Nazis take over Austria, you
will be the entire trumpet section.

1115
01:33:57,070 --> 01:33:58,051
You flatter me.

1116
01:33:59,054 --> 01:34:02,799
Oh, how clumsy of me.
I meant to accuse you.

1117
01:34:10,231 --> 01:34:12,623
It's very kind of you
to offer to help me, baroness.

1118
01:34:12,890 --> 01:34:14,386
I'm delighted, Maria.

1119
01:34:14,844 --> 01:34:18,393
I really don't think I have anything
that would be appropriate.

1120
01:34:18,846 --> 01:34:22,811
Now where is that lovely little thing
you were wearing the other evening?

1121
01:34:23,043 --> 01:34:26,209
When the captain couldn't keep
his eyes off you.

1122
01:34:29,448 --> 01:34:31,206
Couldn't keep his eyes off me?

1123
01:34:32,491 --> 01:34:34,218
Come, my dear, we are women.

1124
01:34:34,445 --> 01:34:37,709
Let's not pretend we don't know
when a man notices us.

1125
01:34:37,937 --> 01:34:41,232
- Here we are.
- The captain notices everybody.

1126
01:34:41,781 --> 01:34:44,115
There's no need to feel
so defensive, Maria.

1127
01:34:44,342 --> 01:34:46,711
You are quite attractive, you know.

1128
01:34:46,937 --> 01:34:50,417
The captain would hardly be a man
if he didn't notice you.

1129
01:34:51,962 --> 01:34:54,234
Baroness, I hope you're joking.

1130
01:34:54,685 --> 01:34:55,896
Not at all.

1131
01:34:56,126 --> 01:34:57,655
I've never done a thing to...

1132
01:34:57,918 --> 01:34:59,414
You don't have to, my dear.

1133
01:35:00,033 --> 01:35:04,673
Nothing's more irresistible to a man
than a woman who's in love with him.

1134
01:35:05,896 --> 01:35:08,234
- In love with him?
- Of course.

1135
01:35:09,131 --> 01:35:12,397
What makes it so nice is
he thinks he's in love with you.

1136
01:35:15,024 --> 01:35:16,552
But that's not true.

1137
01:35:16,945 --> 01:35:20,296
Surely you've noticed the way
he looks into your eyes.

1138
01:35:20,562 --> 01:35:25,269
And you know, you blushed in his arms
when you were dancing just now.

1139
01:35:26,456 --> 01:35:28,083
Don't take it to heart.

1140
01:35:28,348 --> 01:35:30,554
He'll get over it soon enough,
I think.

1141
01:35:30,813 --> 01:35:32,702
Men do, you know.

1142
01:35:33,662 --> 01:35:34,711
Then I should go.

1143
01:35:36,001 --> 01:35:37,376
I mustn't stay here.

1144
01:35:47,436 --> 01:35:50,732
- Is there something I can do to help?
- No, nothing.

1145
01:35:52,431 --> 01:35:53,611
Yes.

1146
01:35:54,578 --> 01:35:56,521
Don't say a word to the captain.

1147
01:35:58,100 --> 01:36:01,520
No, I wouldn't dream of it.

1148
01:36:08,027 --> 01:36:09,523
Goodbye, Maria.

1149
01:36:10,301 --> 01:36:12,987
I'm sure you'll make a very fine nun.

1150
01:36:41,817 --> 01:36:43,729
Champagne, darling.

1151
01:36:44,122 --> 01:36:47,954
I feel like celebrating. Cheers.

1152
01:36:53,219 --> 01:36:56,004
- You know something.
- Perhaps.

1153
01:36:56,229 --> 01:37:00,578
If you're so clever, tell me how to
get fraulein to influence Georg.

1154
01:37:00,809 --> 01:37:03,334
I want those children in the festival.

1155
01:37:03,788 --> 01:37:05,993
Elsa, this is important to Austria.

1156
01:37:06,190 --> 01:37:07,819
Wouldn't do you any harm either.

1157
01:37:08,018 --> 01:37:09,546
I thought of that.

1158
01:37:09,778 --> 01:37:12,145
Well, if it's a matter of influence...

1159
01:37:12,337 --> 01:37:15,123
...maybe the one you have
to be talking to is me.

1160
01:40:31,830 --> 01:40:33,969
- Two.
- Three.

1161
01:40:34,231 --> 01:40:35,662
- Four.
- Five.

1162
01:40:36,859 --> 01:40:38,802
- Six.
- Seven.

1163
01:40:39,068 --> 01:40:40,629
Eight.

1164
01:40:40,862 --> 01:40:42,618
- Four.
- Two.

1165
01:40:43,679 --> 01:40:45,437
- Seven.
- Five.

1166
01:40:45,666 --> 01:40:47,773
- Two.
- Six.

1167
01:40:52,232 --> 01:40:54,176
Isn't this fun?

1168
01:40:55,531 --> 01:40:57,769
- Four.
- I'm number five.

1169
01:40:58,028 --> 01:41:00,103
- Oh, yes.
- Eight.

1170
01:41:00,399 --> 01:41:02,672
- Two.
- Four.

1171
01:41:03,058 --> 01:41:04,236
Six.

1172
01:41:06,611 --> 01:41:07,789
Two.

1173
01:41:08,884 --> 01:41:11,736
Baroness Schraeder, do you mind
if we stop now? We're tired.

1174
01:41:11,959 --> 01:41:13,849
Whatever you want, dear.

1175
01:41:14,105 --> 01:41:16,017
We'll do it again tomorrow.

1176
01:41:25,798 --> 01:41:27,870
The country's so restful, isn't it?

1177
01:41:28,872 --> 01:41:30,432
Have some lemonade.

1178
01:41:31,625 --> 01:41:33,001
There must be an easier way.

1179
01:41:34,346 --> 01:41:37,480
I get a fiendish delight thinking
of you as the mother of seven.

1180
01:41:38,381 --> 01:41:40,141
How do you plan to do it?

1181
01:41:40,400 --> 01:41:42,345
Darling, haven't you ever heard...

1182
01:41:42,610 --> 01:41:45,581
...of a delightful little thing
called boarding school?

1183
01:41:46,679 --> 01:41:48,851
Baroness Machiavelli.

1184
01:41:50,137 --> 01:41:52,048
Uncle Max, where's Father?

1185
01:41:52,314 --> 01:41:54,040
I think he's in the house.

1186
01:41:54,237 --> 01:41:56,693
What's the matter
with all you gloomy pussies?

1187
01:41:56,926 --> 01:41:59,612
- Nothing.
- I know. Let's have a rehearsal.

1188
01:41:59,807 --> 01:42:00,670
What for?

1189
01:42:00,864 --> 01:42:03,258
Let's make believe we're on-stage
at the festival.

1190
01:42:03,463 --> 01:42:07,173
- I don't feel like singing.
- Not without Fraulein Maria.

1191
01:42:07,432 --> 01:42:09,736
Liesl, get the guitar.
Come on, Marta.

1192
01:42:09,931 --> 01:42:12,779
Everybody into the group.
Get in your places.

1193
01:42:13,036 --> 01:42:15,689
Now be cheerful, right?
Give us the key, Liesl.

1194
01:42:17,521 --> 01:42:20,076
Now, impress me.

1195
01:42:23,924 --> 01:42:25,203
Gretl, why don't you sing?

1196
01:42:25,462 --> 01:42:27,830
I can't. I've got a sore finger.

1197
01:42:28,824 --> 01:42:31,761
But you sang so beautifully
the night of the party.

1198
01:42:31,964 --> 01:42:34,202
Come on, all of you.
Try something you know.

1199
01:42:34,430 --> 01:42:35,859
Enjoy it. Be cheerful.

1200
01:42:36,127 --> 01:42:37,689
All right, Liesl.

1201
01:42:39,555 --> 01:42:44,742
The hills are alive

1202
01:42:44,968 --> 01:42:52,328
With the sound of music

1203
01:42:53,485 --> 01:42:58,346
With songs they have sung

1204
01:42:58,579 --> 01:43:06,104
For a thousand years

1205
01:43:06,778 --> 01:43:11,964
The hills fill my heart

1206
01:43:12,189 --> 01:43:19,583
With the sound of music

1207
01:43:19,909 --> 01:43:22,432
They wanted to sing for me,
bless their hearts.

1208
01:43:22,728 --> 01:43:24,550
That's lovely, lovely.
Don't stop.

1209
01:43:28,395 --> 01:43:32,142
- Something long and cool, Georg?
- No, thank you, darling.

1210
01:43:32,530 --> 01:43:34,866
- Father?
- Yes, Brigitta?

1211
01:43:35,282 --> 01:43:37,454
Is it true Fraulein Maria
isn't coming back?

1212
01:43:37,747 --> 01:43:40,719
Yes, I suppose it's true.
What have we got here?

1213
01:43:41,014 --> 01:43:45,523
- Pink lemonade.
- Laced with lemonade.

1214
01:43:46,234 --> 01:43:47,698
I don't believe it, Father.

1215
01:43:49,022 --> 01:43:50,964
- What?
- About Fraulein Maria.

1216
01:43:51,359 --> 01:43:52,537
Oh, Fraulein Maria!

1217
01:43:52,833 --> 01:43:56,154
Didn't I tell you what her note said?
I'm sure I did.

1218
01:43:56,869 --> 01:43:59,260
She said she missed her life
at the abbey.

1219
01:43:59,527 --> 01:44:01,600
She had to leave us.

1220
01:44:01,833 --> 01:44:03,362
And that's all there is to it.

1221
01:44:05,003 --> 01:44:07,590
I think I'm brave enough to try
some of that.

1222
01:44:07,789 --> 01:44:10,411
- She didn't even say goodbye.
- She did in her note.

1223
01:44:10,672 --> 01:44:12,397
That isn't the same thing.

1224
01:44:12,689 --> 01:44:14,251
Not too sweet, not too sour.

1225
01:44:14,964 --> 01:44:16,875
Just too pink.

1226
01:44:18,264 --> 01:44:21,232
Father, who is our new governess
going to be?

1227
01:44:27,615 --> 01:44:28,662
Well...

1228
01:44:30,911 --> 01:44:35,937
...you're not going to have
a governess anymore.

1229
01:44:36,262 --> 01:44:38,819
- We're not?
- No.

1230
01:44:40,939 --> 01:44:42,980
You're going to have a new mother.

1231
01:44:44,045 --> 01:44:45,989
A new mother?

1232
01:44:46,800 --> 01:44:49,803
We talked about it last night.
It's all settled.

1233
01:44:50,003 --> 01:44:52,589
And we're all going to be very happy.

1234
01:45:24,271 --> 01:45:26,641
Well, all right, all right.
Run off and play.

1235
01:45:57,325 --> 01:45:58,252
Yes, my children?

1236
01:45:58,445 --> 01:46:00,749
- My name is Liesl.
- Yes, Liesl?

1237
01:46:01,231 --> 01:46:05,010
We, my brothers and sisters,
want to see Fraulein Maria.

1238
01:46:06,129 --> 01:46:08,042
Fraulein Maria?

1239
01:46:08,787 --> 01:46:10,676
Oh, Maria.

1240
01:46:12,505 --> 01:46:14,261
Come in, please.

1241
01:46:17,979 --> 01:46:19,475
Wait here.

1242
01:46:29,991 --> 01:46:33,026
I'm Sister Margaretta. I understand
you inquired about Maria.

1243
01:46:33,289 --> 01:46:35,680
We have to see her.
Will you tell her we're here?

1244
01:46:35,916 --> 01:46:38,406
- I'm afraid I can't do that.
- But you've got to!

1245
01:46:38,701 --> 01:46:40,679
- She's our governess.
- We want her back.

1246
01:46:40,881 --> 01:46:42,705
She didn't even say goodbye.

1247
01:46:42,930 --> 01:46:44,621
All we want to do is talk to her.

1248
01:46:45,364 --> 01:46:48,150
I'm very sorry,
but Maria is in seclusion.

1249
01:46:48,374 --> 01:46:51,344
- She hasn't been seeing anyone.
- She'll see us.

1250
01:46:51,579 --> 01:46:53,968
I want to show her my finger.

1251
01:46:54,173 --> 01:46:55,995
Some other time, dear.

1252
01:46:56,254 --> 01:46:57,499
I'll tell her you were here.

1253
01:46:57,759 --> 01:47:00,696
- It was sweet of you to call.
- We have to speak to her!

1254
01:47:01,312 --> 01:47:04,317
Run along, children.
Run along home.

1255
01:47:04,519 --> 01:47:06,079
I'm sure she'd like to see us.

1256
01:47:06,343 --> 01:47:08,515
Sister Margaretta, please.

1257
01:47:08,744 --> 01:47:12,328
- Goodbye, children.
- Sister Margaretta, may we, please?

1258
01:47:14,990 --> 01:47:16,649
What was that about, Sister?

1259
01:47:16,880 --> 01:47:18,989
The von Trapp children,
Reverend Mother.

1260
01:47:19,219 --> 01:47:21,553
They want to see Maria.

1261
01:47:21,810 --> 01:47:24,015
Has she spoken yet?
Has she told you anything?

1262
01:47:24,275 --> 01:47:28,108
She doesn't say a word,
Reverend Mother, except in prayer.

1263
01:47:28,375 --> 01:47:29,326
Poor child.

1264
01:47:29,530 --> 01:47:32,380
It's strange.
She seems happy to be back here...

1265
01:47:32,605 --> 01:47:35,771
...and yet she's unhappy too.

1266
01:47:36,992 --> 01:47:39,930
Perhaps I have been wrong
in leaving her alone so long.

1267
01:47:40,196 --> 01:47:42,783
Bring her to me,
even if she's not yet ready.

1268
01:47:42,984 --> 01:47:44,577
Yes, Reverend Mother.

1269
01:47:49,868 --> 01:47:53,219
Sister Augusta, take our new postulant
to the robing room.

1270
01:47:54,190 --> 01:47:56,363
God bless you, my daughter.

1271
01:48:02,325 --> 01:48:03,986
Yes, bring her in.

1272
01:48:12,639 --> 01:48:14,811
You've been unhappy. I'm sorry.

1273
01:48:16,769 --> 01:48:17,916
Reverend Mother.

1274
01:48:18,243 --> 01:48:20,767
Why did they send you back to us?

1275
01:48:21,574 --> 01:48:23,464
They didn't send me back.
I left.

1276
01:48:25,867 --> 01:48:27,363
Sit down, Maria.

1277
01:48:27,853 --> 01:48:29,577
Tell me what happened.

1278
01:48:34,578 --> 01:48:35,857
I was frightened.

1279
01:48:36,115 --> 01:48:40,396
- Frightened? Were they unkind to you.
- Oh, no!

1280
01:48:40,629 --> 01:48:44,178
No, I was confused. I felt...

1281
01:48:45,593 --> 01:48:47,602
I've never felt that way before.

1282
01:48:47,836 --> 01:48:51,451
I couldn't stay. I knew that here
I'd be away from it. I'd be safe.

1283
01:48:51,679 --> 01:48:56,190
Maria, our abbey is not to be used
as an escape.

1284
01:48:56,453 --> 01:48:58,594
What is it you can't face?

1285
01:49:00,486 --> 01:49:01,862
I can't face him again.

1286
01:49:02,664 --> 01:49:04,127
Him?

1287
01:49:05,644 --> 01:49:07,620
Thank you, Sister Margaretta.

1288
01:49:16,852 --> 01:49:18,415
Captain von Trapp?

1289
01:49:23,645 --> 01:49:26,231
- Are you in love with him?
- I don't know!

1290
01:49:26,463 --> 01:49:27,871
I don't know. L...

1291
01:49:28,381 --> 01:49:32,062
The baroness said I was.
She said that he was in love with me.

1292
01:49:32,321 --> 01:49:34,879
But I didn't want to believe it.

1293
01:49:35,910 --> 01:49:38,114
There were times we looked
at each other.

1294
01:49:38,312 --> 01:49:39,807
I could hardly breathe.

1295
01:49:40,169 --> 01:49:42,758
- Did you let him see your feelings?
- I don't know.

1296
01:49:43,341 --> 01:49:45,896
That's what's torturing me.
I was on God's errand.

1297
01:49:46,096 --> 01:49:50,890
To have asked for his love would have
been wrong. I just couldn't stay.

1298
01:49:52,979 --> 01:49:55,664
I'm ready at this moment
to take my vows.

1299
01:49:56,502 --> 01:49:59,439
- Please help me.
- Maria.

1300
01:50:00,954 --> 01:50:05,465
The love of a man and a woman is holy.
You have a great capacity to love.

1301
01:50:05,695 --> 01:50:08,511
You must find out how God
wants you to spend your love.

1302
01:50:08,802 --> 01:50:12,484
But I pledged my life to God.
I pledged my life to his service.

1303
01:50:12,678 --> 01:50:16,871
My daughter, if you love this man,
it doesn't mean you love God less.

1304
01:50:18,475 --> 01:50:20,264
No.

1305
01:50:20,491 --> 01:50:22,282
You must find out.

1306
01:50:23,950 --> 01:50:26,341
You must go back.

1307
01:50:26,608 --> 01:50:28,498
You can't ask me to do that.

1308
01:50:28,690 --> 01:50:31,081
- Please let me stay. I beg...
- Maria.

1309
01:50:31,284 --> 01:50:35,086
These walls were not built
to shut out problems.

1310
01:50:35,289 --> 01:50:36,815
You have to face them.

1311
01:50:37,371 --> 01:50:40,505
You have to live the life
you were born to live.

1312
01:50:46,145 --> 01:50:50,275
Climb every mountain

1313
01:50:50,500 --> 01:50:54,117
Search high and low

1314
01:50:54,343 --> 01:50:58,922
Follow every byway

1315
01:50:59,148 --> 01:51:03,243
Every path you know

1316
01:51:03,665 --> 01:51:07,943
Climb every mountain

1317
01:51:08,210 --> 01:51:12,371
Ford every stream

1318
01:51:12,600 --> 01:51:16,793
Follow every rainbow

1319
01:51:17,051 --> 01:51:21,212
Till you find your dream

1320
01:51:21,407 --> 01:51:24,377
A dream that will need

1321
01:51:24,610 --> 01:51:29,252
All the love you can give

1322
01:51:29,992 --> 01:51:33,256
Every day of your life

1323
01:51:33,515 --> 01:51:39,662
For as long as you live

1324
01:51:39,950 --> 01:51:44,080
Climb every mountain

1325
01:51:44,307 --> 01:51:48,467
Ford every stream

1326
01:51:48,727 --> 01:51:53,106
Follow every rainbow

1327
01:51:53,306 --> 01:52:01,375
Till you find your dream

1328
01:52:02,435 --> 01:52:05,788
A dream that will need

1329
01:52:06,087 --> 01:52:11,394
All the love you can give

1330
01:52:11,659 --> 01:52:15,011
Every day of your life

1331
01:52:15,246 --> 01:52:21,417
For as long as you live

1332
01:52:21,653 --> 01:52:25,908
Climb every mountain

1333
01:52:26,135 --> 01:52:29,912
Ford every stream

1334
01:52:30,552 --> 01:52:34,999
Follow every rainbow

1335
01:52:35,389 --> 01:52:39,321
Till you find...

1336
01:52:39,554 --> 01:52:49,154
...your dream

1337
01:52:51,597 --> 01:52:55,014
Now, it's not like my children
to be secretive.

1338
01:52:55,248 --> 01:52:57,257
We're not being secretive, Father.

1339
01:52:58,867 --> 01:53:02,066
And it's not like my children
to be late for dinner.

1340
01:53:02,325 --> 01:53:05,626
- We lost track of the time.
- I see.

1341
01:53:06,394 --> 01:53:09,658
Who's going to be the first one
to tell me the truth? Friedrich.

1342
01:53:09,918 --> 01:53:11,893
Brigitta. Liesl.

1343
01:53:13,216 --> 01:53:15,354
Where do you think we were, Father?

1344
01:53:21,671 --> 01:53:25,471
If you don't believe us, you must have
some idea of where you think we were.

1345
01:53:28,909 --> 01:53:30,634
- Marta.
- Yes, Father.

1346
01:53:30,831 --> 01:53:32,043
You tell me.

1347
01:53:33,328 --> 01:53:36,813
Friedrich told you, Father.
We were berry picking.

1348
01:53:37,621 --> 01:53:42,096
- I forgot! You were berry picking.
- Yes, we love berry picking.

1349
01:53:42,326 --> 01:53:43,377
All afternoon?

1350
01:53:43,608 --> 01:53:45,267
- We picked thousands.
- Thousands?

1351
01:53:45,466 --> 01:53:48,250
- They were all over the place.
- What kind of berries?

1352
01:53:48,507 --> 01:53:51,643
- Blueberries, sir.
- Blueberries.

1353
01:53:53,505 --> 01:53:56,739
It's too early for blueberries.

1354
01:53:58,181 --> 01:54:00,190
- They were strawberries.
- Strawberries?

1355
01:54:00,872 --> 01:54:03,458
It's been so cold lately,
they turned blue.

1356
01:54:09,071 --> 01:54:11,145
Very well. Show me the berries.

1357
01:54:12,370 --> 01:54:13,516
- We...
- Well...

1358
01:54:13,747 --> 01:54:16,400
- Show me the berries you picked.
- We don't have them.

1359
01:54:16,628 --> 01:54:18,802
You don't have them?
What happened to them?

1360
01:54:19,031 --> 01:54:21,717
- We...
- We ate them.

1361
01:54:21,914 --> 01:54:24,404
- You ate them?
- Yes!

1362
01:54:24,603 --> 01:54:26,131
- They were so good.
- Delicious.

1363
01:54:26,366 --> 01:54:27,512
Very well.

1364
01:54:27,773 --> 01:54:32,699
Since you've obviously stuffed
yourselves on thousands of berries...

1365
01:54:32,929 --> 01:54:36,708
...you can't be hungry anymore,
so I'll have to tell Frau Schmidt...

1366
01:54:36,937 --> 01:54:39,684
...to skip your dinner.

1367
01:54:48,496 --> 01:54:51,184
It's your fault.
We should have told him the truth.

1368
01:54:51,445 --> 01:54:53,330
And made him boiling mad at us?

1369
01:54:53,525 --> 01:54:55,379
It's better than starving to death.

1370
01:54:55,606 --> 01:54:58,357
We didn't do anything wrong.
We just wanted to see her.

1371
01:54:59,610 --> 01:55:02,579
My stomach's making noises.

1372
01:55:03,002 --> 01:55:05,724
The least they could have done
was to let us say hello.

1373
01:55:06,815 --> 01:55:10,561
- I wonder what grass tastes like.
- I feel awful.

1374
01:55:10,980 --> 01:55:15,076
When Fraulein Maria wanted to feel
better she used to sing that song.

1375
01:55:15,655 --> 01:55:17,064
Let's try it.

1376
01:55:17,287 --> 01:55:19,845
Raindrops on roses

1377
01:55:20,138 --> 01:55:24,003
And whiskers on kittens

1378
01:55:24,814 --> 01:55:27,304
Bright copper kettles

1379
01:55:27,505 --> 01:55:30,444
And warm woolen mittens

1380
01:55:31,732 --> 01:55:37,455
Brown paper packages
Tied up with strings

1381
01:55:37,723 --> 01:55:43,477
These are a few of my favorite things

1382
01:55:43,710 --> 01:55:45,654
Why don't I feel better?

1383
01:55:46,784 --> 01:55:48,989
Girls in white dresses

1384
01:55:49,253 --> 01:55:52,221
With blue satin sashes

1385
01:55:52,489 --> 01:55:57,894
Snowflakes that stay
On my nose and eyelashes

1386
01:55:58,251 --> 01:56:01,287
- Silver white winters...
- Fraulein Maria's back!

1387
01:56:01,488 --> 01:56:02,731
...that melt into springs

1388
01:56:03,121 --> 01:56:06,254
These are a few of my favorite things

1389
01:56:06,484 --> 01:56:09,451
When the dog bites
When the bee stings

1390
01:56:09,652 --> 01:56:11,692
When I'm feeling sad

1391
01:56:12,183 --> 01:56:15,034
I simply remember my favorite things

1392
01:56:15,289 --> 01:56:17,462
And then I don't feel

1393
01:56:17,658 --> 01:56:24,157
So bad

1394
01:56:24,385 --> 01:56:27,293
- Children, I'm so glad to see you.
- We missed you.

1395
01:56:27,526 --> 01:56:28,474
I missed you.

1396
01:56:28,742 --> 01:56:30,785
- Kurt, how are you?
- Hungry.

1397
01:56:32,264 --> 01:56:34,788
- What happened to your finger?
- It got caught.

1398
01:56:35,050 --> 01:56:37,125
- Caught in what?
- Friedrich's teeth.

1399
01:56:38,318 --> 01:56:40,390
- Liesl, you all right?
- Just fair.

1400
01:56:40,592 --> 01:56:43,462
- Any telegrams been delivered lately?
- None at all.

1401
01:56:43,699 --> 01:56:46,996
But I'm learning to accept it.
I'll be glad when school begins.

1402
01:56:47,283 --> 01:56:51,795
Liesl, you can't use school to escape
your problems. You have to face them.

1403
01:56:52,027 --> 01:56:53,401
I have so much to tell you.

1404
01:56:53,658 --> 01:56:55,570
We have things to tell you too.

1405
01:56:55,901 --> 01:56:59,449
The most important thing is
that Father is going to be married.

1406
01:56:59,649 --> 01:57:00,663
Married?

1407
01:57:00,993 --> 01:57:02,936
Yes, to Baroness Schraeder.

1408
01:57:10,536 --> 01:57:12,031
Oh, I see.

1409
01:57:13,806 --> 01:57:17,037
Father, look!
Fraulein Maria's back!

1410
01:57:17,262 --> 01:57:19,240
Fraulein Maria's back from the abbey.

1411
01:57:21,364 --> 01:57:22,378
Good evening, captain.

1412
01:57:23,796 --> 01:57:25,039
Good evening.

1413
01:57:27,478 --> 01:57:29,235
Everyone inside for dinner.

1414
01:57:29,528 --> 01:57:31,024
Dinner!

1415
01:57:40,001 --> 01:57:44,546
You left without saying goodbye.
Even to the children.

1416
01:57:45,512 --> 01:57:46,975
It was wrong of me. Forgive me.

1417
01:57:48,937 --> 01:57:50,051
Why did you?

1418
01:57:50,252 --> 01:57:52,970
Please don't ask me.
The reason no longer exists.

1419
01:57:54,094 --> 01:57:57,063
Fraulein Maria, you've returned.

1420
01:57:58,259 --> 01:57:59,985
Isn't it wonderful, Georg?

1421
01:58:03,159 --> 01:58:05,299
I wish you every happiness,
baroness.

1422
01:58:05,529 --> 01:58:08,116
You too, captain.
The children say you're to marry.

1423
01:58:08,348 --> 01:58:09,427
Thank you, my dear.

1424
01:58:11,869 --> 01:58:15,286
You are back to stay?

1425
01:58:17,281 --> 01:58:20,482
Only until arrangements can be made
for another governess.

1426
01:59:13,939 --> 01:59:15,501
There you are.

1427
01:59:29,310 --> 01:59:31,679
I must speak to cook
about the schnitzel.

1428
01:59:31,936 --> 01:59:35,104
It is entirely too delicious
for my figure.

1429
01:59:35,524 --> 01:59:38,342
And it makes you much too quiet
at the dinner table.

1430
01:59:38,600 --> 01:59:40,510
Or was it the wine?

1431
01:59:40,744 --> 01:59:42,502
Undoubtedly the wine.

1432
01:59:44,973 --> 01:59:47,146
You have no idea
the trouble I'm having...

1433
01:59:47,406 --> 01:59:50,027
...trying to decide on
a wedding present for you.

1434
01:59:50,321 --> 01:59:52,399
Oh, I know. I'm enough.

1435
01:59:52,661 --> 01:59:56,107
But I do want you to have
some little trifle for the occasion.

1436
01:59:56,342 --> 01:59:58,580
At first I thought
of a fountain pen...

1437
01:59:58,807 --> 02:00:00,981
...but you've already got one.

1438
02:00:01,242 --> 02:00:04,059
Then I thought perhaps a villa
in the south of France...

1439
02:00:04,285 --> 02:00:06,839
...but they are so difficult
to gift-wrap.

1440
02:00:07,103 --> 02:00:09,407
Oh, Georg, how do you
feel about yachts?

1441
02:00:09,696 --> 02:00:11,871
A long, sleek one
for the Mediterranean...

1442
02:00:12,100 --> 02:00:14,754
...or a tiny one
for your bathtub, huh?

1443
02:00:16,841 --> 02:00:18,783
- Elsa.
- Where to go on our honeymoon?

1444
02:00:19,018 --> 02:00:20,544
Now, that's a real problem.

1445
02:00:20,749 --> 02:00:23,979
A trip around the world
would be lovely. And then I said:

1446
02:00:24,270 --> 02:00:26,990
"Oh, Elsa, there must be
someplace better to go."

1447
02:00:27,248 --> 02:00:29,583
- But don't worry, darling, I'Il...
- Elsa.

1448
02:00:30,228 --> 02:00:31,439
Yes, Georg.

1449
02:00:32,405 --> 02:00:33,681
It's no use...

1450
02:00:34,838 --> 02:00:36,149
...you and I.

1451
02:00:37,658 --> 02:00:40,759
I'm being dishonest to both of us...

1452
02:00:42,046 --> 02:00:43,641
...and utterly unfair to you.

1453
02:00:48,706 --> 02:00:51,329
- When two people talk of marriage...
- No, don't.

1454
02:00:52,166 --> 02:00:54,176
Don't say another word, please.

1455
02:00:57,355 --> 02:01:02,181
You see, there are other things
I've been thinking of.

1456
02:01:03,056 --> 02:01:07,599
Fond as I am of you, I really don't
think you're the right man for me.

1457
02:01:10,035 --> 02:01:12,427
You're much too independent.

1458
02:01:12,727 --> 02:01:17,237
And I need someone
who needs me desperately...

1459
02:01:17,530 --> 02:01:20,403
...or at least needs
my money desperately.

1460
02:01:22,496 --> 02:01:27,201
I've enjoyed every moment we've had
together and I do thank you for that.

1461
02:01:29,862 --> 02:01:31,687
Now, if you'll forgive me...

1462
02:01:31,881 --> 02:01:33,855
...I'll go inside,
pack my little bags...

1463
02:01:34,090 --> 02:01:36,481
...and return to Vienna
where I belong.

1464
02:01:41,648 --> 02:01:43,405
And somewhere out there...

1465
02:01:43,699 --> 02:01:47,892
...is a young lady who, I think...

1466
02:01:48,151 --> 02:01:49,329
...will never be a nun.

1467
02:02:00,992 --> 02:02:03,230
Auf Wiedersehen, darling.

1468
02:02:27,926 --> 02:02:29,042
Hello.

1469
02:02:34,620 --> 02:02:38,073
I thought I just might find you here.

1470
02:02:42,083 --> 02:02:44,257
Was there something you wanted?

1471
02:02:44,679 --> 02:02:47,681
No, no, no. Sit down, please.

1472
02:02:48,586 --> 02:02:49,864
Please.

1473
02:02:54,800 --> 02:02:56,076
May I?

1474
02:03:07,961 --> 02:03:12,506
You know, I was thinking
and I was wondering two things:

1475
02:03:13,630 --> 02:03:17,692
Why did you run away to the abbey?

1476
02:03:18,498 --> 02:03:22,976
And what was it
that made you come back?

1477
02:03:24,586 --> 02:03:28,865
Well, I had an obligation
to fulfill...

1478
02:03:29,068 --> 02:03:31,112
...and I came back to fulfill it.

1479
02:03:31,727 --> 02:03:33,101
Is that all?

1480
02:03:34,384 --> 02:03:36,458
And I missed the children.

1481
02:03:36,788 --> 02:03:37,900
Yes.

1482
02:03:39,126 --> 02:03:41,906
- Only the children?
- No. Yes.

1483
02:03:42,134 --> 02:03:45,814
- Isn't it right that I missed them?
- Oh, yes. Yes, of course.

1484
02:03:46,010 --> 02:03:48,532
I was only hoping that perhaps you...

1485
02:03:49,595 --> 02:03:51,288
Perhaps you might...

1486
02:03:52,958 --> 02:03:54,138
Yes?

1487
02:03:55,842 --> 02:04:00,931
Well, nothing was the same
when you were away...

1488
02:04:01,672 --> 02:04:04,773
...and it'll be all wrong again
after you leave...

1489
02:04:04,971 --> 02:04:09,447
...and I just thought perhaps
you might change your mind.

1490
02:04:13,361 --> 02:04:17,423
Well, I'm sure the baroness will be
able to make things fine for you.

1491
02:04:17,687 --> 02:04:18,963
Maria...

1492
02:04:20,983 --> 02:04:24,336
- There isn't going to be any baroness.
- There isn't?

1493
02:04:26,653 --> 02:04:27,963
No.

1494
02:04:28,255 --> 02:04:29,947
I don't understand.

1495
02:04:32,256 --> 02:04:36,187
Well, we've called off our engagement,
you see, and...

1496
02:04:36,453 --> 02:04:39,772
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Yes. You are?

1497
02:04:40,905 --> 02:04:42,914
- You did?
- Yes.

1498
02:04:44,013 --> 02:04:48,358
Well, you can't marry someone
when you're...

1499
02:04:50,834 --> 02:04:52,810
...in love with someone else...

1500
02:04:56,054 --> 02:04:57,427
...can you?

1501
02:05:30,900 --> 02:05:33,107
The Reverend Mother always says:

1502
02:05:33,334 --> 02:05:36,631
"When the Lord closes a door,
somewhere He opens a window."

1503
02:05:44,254 --> 02:05:47,155
What else does
the Reverend Mother say?

1504
02:05:48,060 --> 02:05:50,362
That you have to look for your life.

1505
02:05:51,965 --> 02:05:54,419
Is that why you came back?

1506
02:05:58,302 --> 02:05:59,707
And have you found it...

1507
02:06:00,669 --> 02:06:01,782
...Maria?

1508
02:06:03,486 --> 02:06:05,394
I think I have.

1509
02:06:08,028 --> 02:06:09,371
I know I have.

1510
02:06:11,775 --> 02:06:13,369
I love you.

1511
02:06:17,179 --> 02:06:18,970
Oh, can this be happening to me?

1512
02:06:22,207 --> 02:06:27,386
Perhaps I had a wicked childhood

1513
02:06:28,828 --> 02:06:33,847
Perhaps I had a miserable youth

1514
02:06:35,645 --> 02:06:41,345
But somewhere
In my wicked, miserable past

1515
02:06:41,823 --> 02:06:47,383
There must have been a moment of truth

1516
02:06:48,284 --> 02:06:54,776
For here you are
Standing there loving me

1517
02:06:55,485 --> 02:07:01,239
Whether or not you should

1518
02:07:01,854 --> 02:07:08,377
So somewhere in my youth or childhood

1519
02:07:09,211 --> 02:07:16,533
I must have done something good

1520
02:07:17,725 --> 02:07:20,573
Nothing comes from nothing

1521
02:07:21,663 --> 02:07:25,369
Nothing ever could

1522
02:07:26,171 --> 02:07:34,683
So somewhere in my youth or childhood

1523
02:07:36,186 --> 02:07:45,299
I must have done something good

1524
02:07:46,140 --> 02:07:50,778
Do you know when I first
started loving you?

1525
02:07:51,165 --> 02:07:54,902
That night at dinner, when you sat
on that ridiculous pine cone.

1526
02:07:55,129 --> 02:07:56,373
What?

1527
02:07:57,658 --> 02:08:00,975
I knew the first time you blew
that silly whistle.

1528
02:08:01,853 --> 02:08:03,763
Oh, my love.

1529
02:08:07,386 --> 02:08:14,970
For here you are
Standing there loving me

1530
02:08:16,859 --> 02:08:22,458
Whether or not you should

1531
02:08:23,773 --> 02:08:30,514
So somewhere in my youth or childhood

1532
02:08:31,294 --> 02:08:38,678
I must have done something good

1533
02:08:39,802 --> 02:08:43,154
Nothing comes from nothing

1534
02:08:43,869 --> 02:08:46,768
Nothing ever could

1535
02:08:47,003 --> 02:08:52,569
So somewhere in my youth...

1536
02:08:52,829 --> 02:08:54,968
...or childhood

1537
02:08:57,946 --> 02:09:04,209
I must have done something

1538
02:09:06,169 --> 02:09:18,292
Something good

1539
02:09:24,731 --> 02:09:26,192
Maria.

1540
02:09:27,962 --> 02:09:32,371
Is there anyone I should go to,
to ask permission to marry you?

1541
02:09:36,122 --> 02:09:38,575
- Why don't we ask...
- The children?

1542
02:11:22,651 --> 02:11:26,511
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

1543
02:11:27,287 --> 02:11:30,833
How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?

1544
02:11:31,772 --> 02:11:35,762
How do you find a word
That means Maria?

1545
02:11:36,183 --> 02:11:37,131
A flibbertigibbet

1546
02:11:37,367 --> 02:11:40,499
A will-o'-the-wisp
A clown

1547
02:11:40,696 --> 02:11:45,072
Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her

1548
02:11:45,495 --> 02:11:49,357
Many a thing she ought to understand

1549
02:11:50,041 --> 02:11:54,165
But how do you make her stay
And listen to all you say?

1550
02:11:54,522 --> 02:11:58,294
How do you keep a wave upon the sand?

1551
02:11:58,617 --> 02:12:03,407
Oh, how do you solve
A problem like Maria?

1552
02:12:03,771 --> 02:12:10,128
How do you hold a moonbeam
In your hand?

1553
02:14:11,063 --> 02:14:12,561
Herr Detweiler!

1554
02:14:15,064 --> 02:14:17,614
- Heil Hitler.
- Oh, good afternoon, Herr Zeller.

1555
02:14:17,848 --> 02:14:21,009
Perhaps you've not heard.
I am now the Gauleiter.

1556
02:14:21,305 --> 02:14:22,768
Heil Hitler.

1557
02:14:23,639 --> 02:14:24,753
Heil Hitler.

1558
02:14:25,049 --> 02:14:27,216
I've come from
Captain von Trapp's house.

1559
02:14:27,636 --> 02:14:31,086
The only one in the area
not flying the Third Reich flag...

1560
02:14:31,319 --> 02:14:32,532
...since the Anschluss.

1561
02:14:32,730 --> 02:14:34,802
- But we have dealt with that.
- I don't...

1562
02:14:35,065 --> 02:14:37,874
The housekeeper told me
that I would find you here.

1563
02:14:38,132 --> 02:14:39,758
The only thing she'd tell me.

1564
02:14:40,244 --> 02:14:42,672
What kind of information
are you looking for?

1565
02:14:42,936 --> 02:14:44,726
When will the captain return?

1566
02:14:45,241 --> 02:14:49,013
Well, he's on his honeymoon trip.
He's not been in touch with us.

1567
02:14:49,236 --> 02:14:53,876
Am I to believe he hasn't communicated
with his children in over a month?

1568
02:14:54,137 --> 02:14:55,957
How many men do you know...

1569
02:14:56,211 --> 02:14:59,376
...who communicate with their children
while honeymooning?

1570
02:15:00,246 --> 02:15:03,795
Upon his return, he'll fill
his proper position in the new order.

1571
02:15:04,088 --> 02:15:06,355
Naturally.
And may I congratulate you...

1572
02:15:06,581 --> 02:15:11,053
...and your people in allowing the
festival to go on tonight as planned.

1573
02:15:11,575 --> 02:15:14,892
Why should it not go on?
Nothing in Austria has changed.

1574
02:15:15,126 --> 02:15:18,389
Singing and music will
show this to the world.

1575
02:15:18,584 --> 02:15:20,207
Austria is the same.

1576
02:15:21,045 --> 02:15:22,357
Heil Hitler.

1577
02:15:24,439 --> 02:15:25,965
Heil Hitler.

1578
02:15:27,572 --> 02:15:28,753
Come, let's go home.

1579
02:15:28,981 --> 02:15:32,332
- Why was he so cross?
- Everybody's cross these days.

1580
02:15:32,536 --> 02:15:35,766
Maybe the flag with the black spider
makes people nervous.

1581
02:15:35,961 --> 02:15:38,774
- Will Father be in trouble?
- He doesn't have to be.

1582
02:15:38,998 --> 02:15:41,616
The thing to do
is to get along with everybody.

1583
02:15:41,849 --> 02:15:43,952
Remember that tonight at the concert.

1584
02:15:44,182 --> 02:15:46,966
Are we really going to sing
before a lot of people?

1585
02:15:47,158 --> 02:15:49,164
Look. The von Trapp Family Singers:

1586
02:15:49,364 --> 02:15:53,775
Liesl, Friedrich, Louisa, Brigitta,
Kurt, Marta and Gretl.

1587
02:15:53,973 --> 02:15:58,162
- Why am I always last?
- Because you are the most important.

1588
02:15:58,839 --> 02:16:00,397
There we go.

1589
02:16:06,039 --> 02:16:09,352
Are you sure Father will approve
of our singing in public?

1590
02:16:09,556 --> 02:16:11,764
He'll be pleased and proud.

1591
02:16:12,216 --> 02:16:14,582
- Liesl, do you think so?
- Don't you trust me?

1592
02:16:14,776 --> 02:16:15,757
No.

1593
02:16:15,959 --> 02:16:17,963
You're a very intelligent girl.

1594
02:16:18,483 --> 02:16:20,557
Liesl. Liesl!

1595
02:16:21,460 --> 02:16:22,608
Rolfe!

1596
02:16:23,576 --> 02:16:25,516
I'm so glad to see you.
It's been su...

1597
02:16:25,720 --> 02:16:26,765
Good afternoon.

1598
02:16:27,158 --> 02:16:29,972
Give this to your father
as soon as he's home.

1599
02:16:30,613 --> 02:16:32,403
- He's on his honeymoon.
- I know.

1600
02:16:32,600 --> 02:16:35,796
- You do?
- We make it our business to know all.

1601
02:16:36,501 --> 02:16:38,958
- Who's "we"?
- See that he gets it.

1602
02:16:39,157 --> 02:16:41,392
- What is it?
- It's a telegram from Berlin.

1603
02:16:42,200 --> 02:16:44,587
Don't you want to deliver it yourself?

1604
02:16:45,048 --> 02:16:47,563
I'm occupied
with more important matters.

1605
02:16:47,763 --> 02:16:50,153
And your father had better be too.

1606
02:16:50,420 --> 02:16:51,851
But, Rolfe!

1607
02:17:14,006 --> 02:17:15,599
Father!

1608
02:17:15,863 --> 02:17:18,414
- We didn't expect you so soon.
- Hello, hello!

1609
02:17:18,642 --> 02:17:21,326
We didn't expect you home
until next week!

1610
02:17:21,524 --> 02:17:26,737
- Did you bring souvenirs from Paris?
- Hello! How are you?

1611
02:17:27,795 --> 02:17:29,041
Why didn't you call us?

1612
02:17:29,238 --> 02:17:31,091
We couldn't get through.

1613
02:17:31,379 --> 02:17:33,239
I had nothing to do with that.

1614
02:17:33,496 --> 02:17:35,437
We came back as fast as we could.

1615
02:17:35,734 --> 02:17:37,804
Well, well, well! We missed you!

1616
02:17:38,035 --> 02:17:40,372
- We missed you!
- We missed kissing you.

1617
02:17:40,562 --> 02:17:43,285
We missed all the noise
in the morning.

1618
02:17:43,543 --> 02:17:47,568
- Mostly, we missed hearing you sing.
- Oh, you came back just in time.

1619
02:17:47,763 --> 02:17:49,454
Look, Fraulein Maria...

1620
02:17:49,652 --> 02:17:51,212
I mean Mother.

1621
02:17:51,604 --> 02:17:53,993
We're going to sing
in the festival tonight.

1622
02:17:54,199 --> 02:17:56,238
We've been having a lovely time!

1623
02:17:56,500 --> 02:17:58,474
We've been rehearsing all...

1624
02:17:59,922 --> 02:18:02,164
Surprise! Surprise!

1625
02:18:02,806 --> 02:18:05,196
Surprises for you on the terrace.

1626
02:18:08,114 --> 02:18:09,456
We'll talk about this.

1627
02:18:09,650 --> 02:18:13,777
I would've told you but you were away.
I had to make a last-minute decision.

1628
02:18:14,036 --> 02:18:16,428
I was fortunate to enter them at all.

1629
02:18:16,660 --> 02:18:21,199
They'll be the talk of the festival.
Imagine, seven children in one family!

1630
02:18:21,393 --> 02:18:22,956
Max!

1631
02:18:23,542 --> 02:18:26,259
Somehow I recall having made it
quite clear to you...

1632
02:18:26,517 --> 02:18:29,071
...how I feel about my family
singing in public!

1633
02:18:29,333 --> 02:18:30,956
The committee was enchanted.

1634
02:18:31,157 --> 02:18:34,192
- What did they say?
- I have never heard such enthusiasm.

1635
02:18:34,454 --> 02:18:38,574
- Don't you think just this once...?
- Absolutely out of the question.

1636
02:18:38,802 --> 02:18:42,765
- Georg, this is for Austria.
- For Austria?

1637
02:18:43,126 --> 02:18:46,259
- There is no Austria!
- But the Anschluss was peaceful.

1638
02:18:46,486 --> 02:18:49,796
- Let's at least be grateful for that.
- Grateful?

1639
02:18:51,603 --> 02:18:53,199
You know, Max...

1640
02:18:54,037 --> 02:18:57,166
...sometimes I don't believe
I know you.

1641
02:18:59,731 --> 02:19:01,039
Father, I forgot.

1642
02:19:01,843 --> 02:19:03,372
This is for you.

1643
02:19:12,757 --> 02:19:16,586
Maria, he has got to at least pretend
to work with these people.

1644
02:19:16,852 --> 02:19:18,313
You must convince him.

1645
02:19:18,515 --> 02:19:21,165
Max, I can't ask him
to be less than he is.

1646
02:19:21,395 --> 02:19:24,561
Then I'll talk to him.
If the children don't sing, well...

1647
02:19:24,820 --> 02:19:26,958
...it will be a reflection
on Austria.

1648
02:19:27,730 --> 02:19:30,958
Oh, I know.
It wouldn't do me any good either.

1649
02:19:35,924 --> 02:19:38,475
Mother? That sounds so nice.

1650
02:19:38,737 --> 02:19:41,356
- I like calling you "Mother."
- I like hearing it.

1651
02:19:41,553 --> 02:19:45,134
You love Father very much.
I can tell you do.

1652
02:19:45,334 --> 02:19:46,096
Very much.

1653
02:19:46,356 --> 02:19:49,519
Mother, what do you do when you
think you love someone?

1654
02:19:50,192 --> 02:19:55,283
I mean, when you stop loving someone
or he stops loving you?

1655
02:19:57,778 --> 02:19:59,753
Well, you cry a little.

1656
02:20:00,177 --> 02:20:02,187
Then you wait for the sun to come out.

1657
02:20:02,485 --> 02:20:03,763
It always does.

1658
02:20:04,021 --> 02:20:07,433
There are so many things I think
I should know but I don't.

1659
02:20:07,634 --> 02:20:09,523
- I really don't.
- How can you?

1660
02:20:09,778 --> 02:20:11,883
Sometimes I feel the world is ending.

1661
02:20:12,117 --> 02:20:15,215
- Then you feel it's just beginning?
- Yes!

1662
02:20:15,413 --> 02:20:19,470
It was that way with me. And for you
it will be just as wonderful.

1663
02:20:20,114 --> 02:20:21,936
Do you really think so?

1664
02:20:22,804 --> 02:20:26,578
When you're 16 going on 17

1665
02:20:26,836 --> 02:20:30,281
Waiting for life to start

1666
02:20:30,928 --> 02:20:34,609
Somebody kind
Who touches your mind

1667
02:20:34,834 --> 02:20:38,957
Will suddenly touch your heart

1668
02:20:39,379 --> 02:20:41,002
When that happens

1669
02:20:41,456 --> 02:20:43,315
After it happens

1670
02:20:43,541 --> 02:20:47,249
Nothing is quite the same

1671
02:20:47,473 --> 02:20:48,967
Somehow I know

1672
02:20:49,234 --> 02:20:51,273
I'll jump up and go

1673
02:20:51,475 --> 02:20:55,601
If ever he calls my name

1674
02:20:55,861 --> 02:20:59,600
Gone are your old ideas of life

1675
02:20:59,857 --> 02:21:03,885
The old ideas grow dim

1676
02:21:04,115 --> 02:21:08,336
Lo and behold
You're someone's wife

1677
02:21:09,233 --> 02:21:14,985
And you belong to him

1678
02:21:15,283 --> 02:21:19,405
You may think this kind of adventure

1679
02:21:19,599 --> 02:21:23,312
Never may come to you

1680
02:21:24,371 --> 02:21:29,519
Darling, 16 going on 17

1681
02:21:30,320 --> 02:21:34,286
Wait a year...

1682
02:21:35,060 --> 02:21:40,077
- I'll wait a year
...or two

1683
02:21:40,497 --> 02:21:47,536
Just wait a year...

1684
02:21:48,368 --> 02:21:56,652
...or two

1685
02:21:58,960 --> 02:22:00,487
Liesl.

1686
02:22:16,275 --> 02:22:17,551
What is it?

1687
02:22:18,447 --> 02:22:19,758
Berlin.

1688
02:22:20,209 --> 02:22:22,000
They've offered me a commission.

1689
02:22:22,259 --> 02:22:24,680
I've been requested
to accept immediately...

1690
02:22:24,915 --> 02:22:28,743
...and report to their naval base
at Bremerhaven tomorrow.

1691
02:22:29,327 --> 02:22:33,159
I knew this would happen.
I didn't think it would be so soon.

1692
02:22:33,395 --> 02:22:36,744
To refuse them would be fatal
for all of us.

1693
02:22:37,936 --> 02:22:41,548
And joining them would be unthinkable.

1694
02:22:47,475 --> 02:22:49,163
Get the children all together.

1695
02:22:49,488 --> 02:22:52,556
Don't say anything to worry them.
Just get them ready.

1696
02:22:53,490 --> 02:22:55,758
We've got to get out of Austria...

1697
02:22:57,362 --> 02:22:58,953
...and this house...

1698
02:23:01,197 --> 02:23:02,576
...tonight.

1699
02:23:44,690 --> 02:23:46,991
This strains my back
and breaks my heart...

1700
02:23:47,248 --> 02:23:49,963
...when I think of the children
missing the festival.

1701
02:23:50,255 --> 02:23:52,811
By your announcement
we'll be over the border.

1702
02:23:53,043 --> 02:23:55,375
Do you appreciate
the sacrifice I'm making?

1703
02:23:55,570 --> 02:23:56,813
You have no choice.

1704
02:23:57,039 --> 02:23:59,755
I know. That's why I'm making it.

1705
02:24:00,432 --> 02:24:02,471
Why doesn't Father turn the motor on?

1706
02:24:02,672 --> 02:24:05,968
Because he doesn't want anyone
to hear us.

1707
02:24:09,454 --> 02:24:11,788
What will Frau Schmidt and Franz say?

1708
02:24:12,047 --> 02:24:15,432
They'll be able to answer honestly
they didn't know anything.

1709
02:24:15,635 --> 02:24:19,690
- Will we be coming back here?
- Someday, Liesl. I do hope someday.

1710
02:24:19,919 --> 02:24:24,656
Are Father and Uncle Max going to push
the car all the way to Switzerland?

1711
02:24:50,349 --> 02:24:52,653
Something wrong
with your car, captain?

1712
02:24:52,975 --> 02:24:55,148
Yes, we couldn't get it started.

1713
02:24:58,767 --> 02:24:59,945
Karl.

1714
02:25:01,838 --> 02:25:05,190
Fix Captain von Trapp's car
so that it will start.

1715
02:25:27,438 --> 02:25:29,160
Excellent, Karl.

1716
02:25:32,400 --> 02:25:35,433
I've not asked you where you
and your family are going.

1717
02:25:35,922 --> 02:25:37,961
Nor have you asked me why I'm here.

1718
02:25:38,160 --> 02:25:41,769
Apparently we both suffer
from a deplorable lack of curiosity.

1719
02:25:42,609 --> 02:25:44,976
You never answered the telegram...

1720
02:25:45,201 --> 02:25:48,362
...from the Admiral of the Navy
of the Third Reich.

1721
02:25:48,587 --> 02:25:50,958
I was under the impression,
Herr Zeller...

1722
02:25:51,214 --> 02:25:54,563
...that the contents of telegrams
in Austria are private!

1723
02:25:55,249 --> 02:25:58,626
At least, the Austria I know.

1724
02:25:59,728 --> 02:26:01,285
I have my orders...

1725
02:26:01,515 --> 02:26:03,591
...to take you
to Bremerhaven tonight...

1726
02:26:03,857 --> 02:26:05,963
...where you will accept
your commission.

1727
02:26:07,056 --> 02:26:12,271
I'm afraid that's going to be
quite impossible.

1728
02:26:12,847 --> 02:26:14,505
You see, we...

1729
02:26:15,056 --> 02:26:17,772
...all of us, the entire family,
will be...

1730
02:26:18,797 --> 02:26:20,737
...singing in the festival tonight.

1731
02:26:21,037 --> 02:26:23,405
As a matter of fact, we're going now.

1732
02:26:24,018 --> 02:26:26,765
We couldn't possibly
let them down now.

1733
02:26:26,960 --> 02:26:29,804
- I just hope we're not too late.
- Yes.

1734
02:26:30,029 --> 02:26:32,813
You ask me to believe that you,
Captain von Trapp...

1735
02:26:33,040 --> 02:26:34,445
...are singing in a concert?

1736
02:26:34,830 --> 02:26:38,789
Believe me, it will be a performance
beyond anything even I've dreamt of.

1737
02:26:39,150 --> 02:26:43,591
Like you, Herr Zeller,
I, too, am a man of hidden talents.

1738
02:26:44,271 --> 02:26:45,549
Yes.

1739
02:26:45,808 --> 02:26:48,195
Here, program.

1740
02:26:53,008 --> 02:26:55,245
It says only the names
of the children.

1741
02:26:55,473 --> 02:26:58,600
It says
the von Trapp Family Singers...

1742
02:26:58,827 --> 02:27:01,761
...and I am the head of
the von Trapp family, am I not?

1743
02:27:03,950 --> 02:27:07,596
And these travel clothes
that you're all wearing?

1744
02:27:08,400 --> 02:27:09,858
Our costumes, naturally.

1745
02:27:10,126 --> 02:27:13,389
This night air is not good
for the children's voices.

1746
02:27:19,373 --> 02:27:22,757
Well, a slight delay in my orders
will not be serious.

1747
02:27:23,919 --> 02:27:25,381
Therefore...

1748
02:27:26,192 --> 02:27:27,750
...you will sing.

1749
02:27:28,653 --> 02:27:30,562
You will all sing.

1750
02:27:30,924 --> 02:27:33,348
But only because that's what I want.

1751
02:27:34,255 --> 02:27:37,550
It will demonstrate that nothing
in Austria has changed.

1752
02:27:38,254 --> 02:27:40,356
And when you have finished singing...

1753
02:27:40,652 --> 02:27:43,687
...you, Captain von Trapp, will be
taken to Bremerhaven.

1754
02:27:44,908 --> 02:27:47,530
Now, if you will all get
into your car...

1755
02:27:47,759 --> 02:27:51,434
...we will escort the von Trapp Family
Singers to the festival.

1756
02:27:52,269 --> 02:27:54,343
No escort will be necessary.

1757
02:27:54,574 --> 02:27:56,961
Necessary? A pleasure, captain.

1758
02:27:57,839 --> 02:28:01,545
After all, we would not want you
to get lost in the crowds.

1759
02:28:02,734 --> 02:28:04,163
Would we?

1760
02:28:04,814 --> 02:28:05,929
No.

1761
02:28:21,484 --> 02:28:24,519
Sew, a needle pulling thread

1762
02:28:24,717 --> 02:28:27,784
La, a note to follow sew

1763
02:28:28,045 --> 02:28:31,361
Tea, a drink with jam and bread

1764
02:28:31,565 --> 02:28:35,207
A drink with jam and bread

1765
02:28:44,398 --> 02:28:46,471
Tea with jam
Jam and bread

1766
02:28:52,105 --> 02:28:55,304
- With jam
- A, B, C

1767
02:28:55,535 --> 02:28:58,633
- With jam
- Do-re-mi

1768
02:28:58,829 --> 02:29:02,273
Tea with jam and bread

1769
02:29:02,508 --> 02:29:03,786
With jam and bread

1770
02:29:04,046 --> 02:29:05,508
With jam
With jam...

1771
02:29:05,711 --> 02:29:14,154
...and bread

1772
02:29:35,243 --> 02:29:38,246
My fellow Austrians...

1773
02:29:39,466 --> 02:29:43,843
...I shall not be seeing you again,
perhaps for a very long time.

1774
02:29:45,195 --> 02:29:46,790
I would like to sing for you now...

1775
02:29:48,331 --> 02:29:49,826
...a love song.

1776
02:29:51,722 --> 02:29:53,831
I know you share this love.

1777
02:29:55,085 --> 02:29:58,630
I pray that you will never let it die.

1778
02:30:10,890 --> 02:30:14,274
Edelweiss

1779
02:30:14,476 --> 02:30:17,542
Edelweiss

1780
02:30:17,804 --> 02:30:23,303
Every morning you greet me

1781
02:30:23,694 --> 02:30:26,628
Small and white

1782
02:30:26,892 --> 02:30:29,542
Clean and bright

1783
02:30:30,089 --> 02:30:34,979
You look happy to meet me

1784
02:30:35,725 --> 02:30:37,666
Blossom of snow

1785
02:30:37,932 --> 02:30:41,376
May you bloom and grow

1786
02:30:41,609 --> 02:30:47,044
Bloom and grow forever

1787
02:30:48,491 --> 02:30:50,879
Edelweiss

1788
02:30:51,113 --> 02:30:53,636
Edelweiss

1789
02:30:53,835 --> 02:30:59,585
Bless my homeland forever

1790
02:31:03,917 --> 02:31:06,884
Edelweiss

1791
02:31:07,115 --> 02:31:08,392
Edel...

1792
02:31:15,466 --> 02:31:18,433
Small and white

1793
02:31:18,635 --> 02:31:21,380
Clean and bright

1794
02:31:21,608 --> 02:31:26,732
You look happy to meet me

1795
02:31:27,530 --> 02:31:29,418
Blossom of snow

1796
02:31:29,611 --> 02:31:32,874
May you bloom and grow

1797
02:31:33,515 --> 02:31:39,265
Bloom and grow forever

1798
02:31:39,723 --> 02:31:42,505
Edelweiss

1799
02:31:42,795 --> 02:31:45,445
Edelweiss

1800
02:31:46,028 --> 02:31:53,924
Bless my homeland forever

1801
02:32:10,920 --> 02:32:12,414
I think it'll work.

1802
02:32:13,130 --> 02:32:14,823
I shall miss all of you.

1803
02:32:15,306 --> 02:32:17,640
I shall miss the money
I could have made with you.

1804
02:32:20,905 --> 02:32:22,399
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

1805
02:32:23,113 --> 02:32:25,666
The competition has come
to its conclusion...

1806
02:32:25,932 --> 02:32:28,899
...except, we don't know
yet what that conclusion will be.

1807
02:32:29,836 --> 02:32:32,254
And while the judges
arrive at their decision...

1808
02:32:32,522 --> 02:32:35,423
...I have been given permission
to offer you an encore.

1809
02:32:35,690 --> 02:32:38,756
This will be the last opportunity
the von Trapps will have...

1810
02:32:38,986 --> 02:32:41,285
...of singing together
for a long, long time.

1811
02:32:42,312 --> 02:32:46,143
Even now, officials are waiting
in this auditorium...

1812
02:32:46,410 --> 02:32:49,028
...to escort Captain von Trapp
to his new command...

1813
02:32:49,226 --> 02:32:52,642
...in the naval forces
of the Third Reich.

1814
02:32:57,131 --> 02:33:01,467
And so, ladies and gentlemen,
the family von Trapp again...

1815
02:33:02,088 --> 02:33:04,263
...to bid you farewell.

1816
02:33:11,208 --> 02:33:14,656
There's a sad sort of clanging
From the clock in the hall

1817
02:33:14,923 --> 02:33:18,119
And the bells in the steeple too

1818
02:33:18,602 --> 02:33:22,312
And up in the nursery
An absurd little bird

1819
02:33:22,505 --> 02:33:24,838
Is popping out to say "coo-coo"

1820
02:33:25,035 --> 02:33:26,628
Coo-coo

1821
02:33:26,891 --> 02:33:27,836
Coo-coo

1822
02:33:28,105 --> 02:33:29,631
Regretfully they tell us

1823
02:33:29,833 --> 02:33:31,553
But firmly they compel us

1824
02:33:31,781 --> 02:33:34,437
To say goodbye

1825
02:33:34,634 --> 02:33:39,587
To you

1826
02:33:42,440 --> 02:33:45,822
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, good night

1827
02:33:46,091 --> 02:33:49,667
We hate to go
And miss this pretty sight

1828
02:33:55,592 --> 02:33:59,041
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, adieu

1829
02:33:59,242 --> 02:34:02,755
Adieu, adieu
To you and you and you

1830
02:34:08,808 --> 02:34:12,254
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye

1831
02:34:12,488 --> 02:34:14,016
We flit, we float

1832
02:34:14,281 --> 02:34:15,873
We fleetly flee, we fly

1833
02:34:21,989 --> 02:34:25,635
So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye

1834
02:34:25,830 --> 02:34:29,061
The sun has gone to bed
And so must I

1835
02:34:29,322 --> 02:34:32,965
Goodbye

1836
02:34:33,194 --> 02:34:38,660
Goodbye

1837
02:34:38,888 --> 02:34:43,874
Goodbye

1838
02:34:44,104 --> 02:34:50,975
Goodbye

1839
02:35:21,478 --> 02:35:25,441
Ladies and gentlemen, I have here the
decision of our distinguished judges.

1840
02:35:25,640 --> 02:35:28,095
We will start with the award
for third prize.

1841
02:35:28,713 --> 02:35:30,946
For this honor,
the judges have named...

1842
02:35:31,208 --> 02:35:35,616
...the first soloist of the choir
of St. Agatha's Church in Murback.

1843
02:35:35,878 --> 02:35:38,018
Fraulein Schweiger.

1844
02:36:13,449 --> 02:36:17,223
Second prize
to The Toby Reiser Quintet.

1845
02:36:44,037 --> 02:36:48,032
And the first prize,
the highest honor in all Austria...

1846
02:36:48,263 --> 02:36:51,228
...the von Trapp Family Singers.

1847
02:37:03,113 --> 02:37:04,704
The family von Trapp.

1848
02:37:18,728 --> 02:37:19,742
They're gone!

1849
02:37:37,671 --> 02:37:39,044
Come with me.

1850
02:37:42,726 --> 02:37:44,637
Quickly, quickly.

1851
02:37:45,510 --> 02:37:47,615
I have a place you can hide.

1852
02:37:48,327 --> 02:37:51,456
Slowly, slowly.

1853
02:38:01,987 --> 02:38:03,617
Open this gate.

1854
02:38:04,711 --> 02:38:06,236
Good evening.

1855
02:38:08,647 --> 02:38:10,019
Hurry up, woman.

1856
02:38:29,061 --> 02:38:30,272
Two men in there.

1857
02:38:30,472 --> 02:38:32,255
Six of you cover the yard.

1858
02:38:32,483 --> 02:38:34,626
You two, cover the corridor.

1859
02:38:48,517 --> 02:38:51,928
Reverend Mother, we didn't realize
we put the abbey in this danger.

1860
02:38:52,192 --> 02:38:54,619
No, Maria, it was right for you
to come here.

1861
02:38:54,822 --> 02:38:56,645
We thought we might borrow
your car.

1862
02:38:56,839 --> 02:38:58,661
I'm afraid our car will do you
no good now.

1863
02:38:59,236 --> 02:39:00,832
I've been listening to the wires.

1864
02:39:01,031 --> 02:39:03,451
The borders have just been closed.

1865
02:39:09,063 --> 02:39:11,264
All right,
if the borders are closed...

1866
02:39:12,513 --> 02:39:15,680
...then we'll drive up into the hills
and go over the mountains on foot.

1867
02:39:16,260 --> 02:39:18,170
- The children...
- We'll help them.

1868
02:39:18,435 --> 02:39:20,509
We can do it without help, Father.

1869
02:39:21,508 --> 02:39:22,817
Maria.

1870
02:39:23,524 --> 02:39:26,013
You will not be alone.
Remember:

1871
02:39:26,245 --> 02:39:29,211
"I will lift up mine eyes unto
the hills from whence cometh my help."

1872
02:39:30,148 --> 02:39:31,196
Yes, Mother.

1873
02:39:32,514 --> 02:39:34,588
- I'm scared.
- Me too.

1874
02:39:46,182 --> 02:39:47,294
God be with you.

1875
02:39:53,957 --> 02:39:55,450
- Mother.
- Yes?

1876
02:39:55,683 --> 02:39:58,750
Would it help if we sang
about our favorite things?

1877
02:39:58,981 --> 02:40:01,847
No, darling.
This is one time it would not help.

1878
02:40:02,114 --> 02:40:05,183
You must be very quiet.
Hold tight to me.

1879
02:42:14,341 --> 02:42:15,518
Let's try the roof.

1880
02:43:09,475 --> 02:43:11,613
Rolfe, please.

1881
02:43:16,513 --> 02:43:17,942
No, wait.

1882
02:43:27,363 --> 02:43:28,639
Maria.

1883
02:43:29,666 --> 02:43:31,041
Children.

1884
02:43:34,914 --> 02:43:37,816
It's you we want, not them.

1885
02:43:38,178 --> 02:43:39,838
Put that down.

1886
02:43:40,864 --> 02:43:44,029
Not another move,
or I'll shoot.

1887
02:43:45,665 --> 02:43:47,607
You're only a boy.

1888
02:43:50,499 --> 02:43:54,012
- You don't really belong to them.
- Stay where you are.

1889
02:43:55,712 --> 02:43:57,625
Come away with us.

1890
02:43:58,817 --> 02:43:59,931
Before it's too late.

1891
02:44:00,512 --> 02:44:02,746
Not another step.
I'll kill you.

1892
02:44:04,962 --> 02:44:08,157
- You give that to me, Rolfe.
- Did you hear me?

1893
02:44:09,123 --> 02:44:10,615
I'll kill you.

1894
02:44:12,417 --> 02:44:13,824
Rolfe.

1895
02:44:31,459 --> 02:44:32,731
You'll never be one of them.

1896
02:44:35,392 --> 02:44:37,018
Lieutenant!

1897
02:44:37,282 --> 02:44:38,360
They're here!

1898
02:44:38,562 --> 02:44:40,056
They're here, lieutenant!

1899
02:45:19,681 --> 02:45:21,273
Reverend Mother.

1900
02:45:22,495 --> 02:45:24,251
I have sinned.

1901
02:45:25,379 --> 02:45:27,451
I too, Reverend Mother.

1902
02:45:29,026 --> 02:45:31,263
What is this sin, my children?

1903
02:46:48,005 --> 02:46:58,951
THE END
